# MAVLink
https://mavlink.io

MAVLink is a lightweight messaging protocol designed to communicate with drones. While we don't have a drone per se, this protocol is design to solve a lot of the problems that we are facing: reliable communications over a radio link.

MAVLink is not only limited to radio. Pretty much, it can be used with anything that exposes a byte stream. Therefore, MAVLink packets can be sent over Serial, TCP, UDP, etc.

## Rocket-Code
- `RadioMAVLink` and `TcpMAVLink` contain any code to read MAVLink packets from the network.
- `GroundComm` contains any general logic for ground station communication. For example, send MAVLink heartbeats. Templates are used to choose to extend either `RadioMAVLink` or `TcpMAVLink`.
- Project specific logic goes into `HotFireGroundComm` or `FillCartGroundComm`.

## Routing
MAVLink doesn't need to be limited to ground station communication. The protocol has a *systemd id* and *component id*  that can be used to target a specific system. Therefore, MAVLink could even be used to communicate across components on the rocket itself, say with the IO proxy. A simple router similar to the [one Ardupilot has](https://ardupilot.org/dev/docs/mavlink-routing-in-ardupilot.html) could also be developed if the number of components starts to get large.

# Radio Communication
- Single RFD900+ on the Ground Station acting as a base (Node 0).
- One RFD900+ on the rocket (Node 1).
- One RFD900+ on the fill-cart (Node 2).
- Node 0 is set to broadcast.
- Node 1 sends to Node 0.
- Node 2 sends to Node 0.
- Filtering on Node 1 and Node 2 is done inside the code using MAVLink's system/component.

## Background

The RFD900+ supports multi-point networking. While doing this, one station acts as a "base" and always must be kept in range of all other nodes. The reason why the base is needed is that the RFD900 does some frequency hopping, so the base is there to synchronize all the radios together.

## Relay/Repeater

It's unclear if it's possible to have one RFD900+ act as a repeater. The manual doesn't specify any of this.

However, the RFD900x [multipoint manual](http://files.rfdesign.com.au/Files/documents/RFD900x%20Multipoint%20User%20Manual%20V1.0.pdf) has an example how to configure a relay. This could potentially allow for a radio to be placed say on a drone and increase our range.
